editorial:
**Approach — pair each push with current min**: Store `[value, minSoFar]` in a single stack. Top, push, pop are trivially O(1).

```javascript
function runOps(ops) {
  class MinStack {
    constructor() { this.stack = []; }
    push(x) {
      const min = this.stack.length === 0 ? x : Math.min(x, this.stack[this.stack.length - 1][1]);
      this.stack.push([x, min]);
    }
    pop() { this.stack.pop(); }
    top() { return this.stack[this.stack.length - 1][0]; }
    getMin() { return this.stack[this.stack.length - 1][1]; }
  }
  let s = null;
  const out = [];
  for (const op of ops) {
    if (op[0] === 'MinStack') { s = new MinStack(); out.push(null); }
    else if (op[0] === 'push') { s.push(op[1]); out.push(null); }
    else if (op[0] === 'pop') { s.pop(); out.push(null); }
    else if (op[0] === 'top') { out.push(s.top()); }
    else if (op[0] === 'getMin') { out.push(s.getMin()); }
  }
  return out;
}
```

**Time**: O(1) per op. **Space**: O(n).

Alternative — auxiliary mins stack only pushing when new ≤ current min: saves space when distinct mins are few but adds equality care.

