editorial:
**Approach — costly push with single queue**: After enqueueing, rotate the queue n-1 times so the just-pushed item is at the front. Now `pop` and `top` are O(1) on a regular FIFO.

```javascript
function runOps(ops) {
  class MyStack {
    constructor() { this.q = []; }
    push(x) {
      this.q.push(x);
      for (let i = 0; i < this.q.length - 1; i++) this.q.push(this.q.shift());
    }
    pop() { return this.q.shift(); }
    top() { return this.q[0]; }
    empty() { return this.q.length === 0; }
  }
  let s = null;
  const out = [];
  for (const op of ops) {
    if (op[0] === 'MyStack') { s = new MyStack(); out.push(null); }
    else if (op[0] === 'push') { s.push(op[1]); out.push(null); }
    else if (op[0] === 'pop') { out.push(s.pop()); }
    else if (op[0] === 'top') { out.push(s.top()); }
    else if (op[0] === 'empty') { out.push(s.empty()); }
  }
  return out;
}
```

**Time**: O(n) push, O(1) pop/top/empty. **Space**: O(n).

Problem says 'two queues' — the spirit is the rotation; in JS `Array.shift()` simulates queue dequeue cleanly.

