editorial:
**Approach — binary search per key**: Keep `Map<key, [ts, val][]>`. Since timestamps are strictly increasing per key, `set` just appends. `get` binary-searches the rightmost ts ≤ query.

```javascript
function runOps(ops) {
  class TimeMap {
    constructor() { this.m = new Map(); }
    set(k, v, t) {
      if (!this.m.has(k)) this.m.set(k, []);
      this.m.get(k).push([t, v]);
    }
    get(k, t) {
      const arr = this.m.get(k);
      if (!arr) return '';
      let lo = 0, hi = arr.length - 1, ans = -1;
      while (lo <= hi) {
        const mid = (lo + hi) >> 1;
        if (arr[mid][0] <= t) { ans = mid; lo = mid + 1; }
        else hi = mid - 1;
      }
      return ans === -1 ? '' : arr[ans][1];
    }
  }
  let tm = null;
  const out = [];
  for (const op of ops) {
    if (op[0] === 'TimeMap') { tm = new TimeMap(); out.push(null); }
    else if (op[0] === 'set') { tm.set(op[1], op[2], op[3]); out.push(null); }
    else if (op[0] === 'get') { out.push(tm.get(op[1], op[2])); }
  }
  return out;
}
```

**Time**: O(1) set, O(log n) get. **Space**: O(n).

