**Approach — small dataset, simple filter+sort**: With ≤ 100 sentences, recompute matches on every keystroke. For larger N, use a Trie where each node holds the top-3 sentences by freq.

```javascript
function runOps(ops) {
  class AutocompleteSystem {
    constructor(sentences, counts) {
      this.freq = new Map();
      for (let i = 0; i < sentences.length; i++) this.freq.set(sentences[i], counts[i]);
      this.buf = '';
    }
    input(c) {
      if (c === '#') {
        this.freq.set(this.buf, (this.freq.get(this.buf) || 0) + 1);
        this.buf = '';
        return [];
      }
      this.buf += c;
      const matches = [];
      for (const [s, f] of this.freq) if (s.startsWith(this.buf)) matches.push([s, f]);
      matches.sort((a, b) => b[1] - a[1] || (a[0] < b[0] ? -1 : a[0] > b[0] ? 1 : 0));
      return matches.slice(0, 3).map(x => x[0]);
    }
  }
  let ac = null;
  const out = [];
  for (const op of ops) {
    if (op[0] === 'AutocompleteSystem') { ac = new AutocompleteSystem(op[1], op[2]); out.push(null); }
    else if (op[0] === 'input') { out.push(ac.input(op[1])); }
  }
  return out;
}
```

**Time**: O(N * L) per keystroke (N = stored sentences, L = max length). **Space**: O(N * L).

Production systems use a Trie + per-node heap of top-K to make each keystroke O(prefix length).

