**Approach — last-printed map**: `Map<msg, ts>`. Print-decision: `!has || now - last >= 10`. On print, update. `purge(now)` iterates and deletes entries with `ts <= now - 10`.

```javascript
function runOps(ops) {
  class Logger {
    constructor() { this.last = new Map(); }
    shouldPrintMessage(t, msg) {
      if (!this.last.has(msg) || t - this.last.get(msg) >= 10) {
        this.last.set(msg, t);
        return true;
      }
      return false;
    }
    purge(t) {
      let evicted = 0;
      const cutoff = t - 10;
      for (const [m, ts] of this.last) {
        if (ts <= cutoff) {
          this.last.delete(m);
          evicted++;
        }
      }
      return evicted;
    }
  }
  let lg = null;
  const out = [];
  for (const op of ops) {
    if (op[0] === 'Logger') { lg = new Logger(); out.push(null); }
    else if (op[0] === 'shouldPrintMessage') { out.push(lg.shouldPrintMessage(op[1], op[2])); }
    else if (op[0] === 'purge') { out.push(lg.purge(op[1])); }
  }
  return out;
}
```

**Time**: O(1) per shouldPrintMessage; O(M) per purge where M = current map size. **Space**: O(M).

For a tighter bound on memory growth, you can purge lazily inside shouldPrintMessage too. The boundary is `>= 10` (so t=10 message at t=0 is allowed) — careful with `>` vs `>=`.
